 {"id":"cass_memory_system-4gw","title":"[Decay] checkForPromotion - Automatic maturity advancement","description":"Automatically advance bullets from candidate → established → proven based on effective score AND recent feedback activity.

COMPLETE IMPLEMENTATION:
```typescript
/**
 * Check if bullet qualifies for promotion to higher maturity level.
 * Promotion requires BOTH sufficient score AND recent helpful marks.
 */
function checkForPromotion(bullet: PlaybookBullet): BulletMaturity {
  const score = getEffectiveScore(bullet);
  const recentHelpful = bullet.helpfulEvents.filter(e =>
    daysSince(e.timestamp) < 30
  ).length;

  // candidate → established: score >= 2 AND recent helpful
  if (bullet.maturity === 'candidate' && score >= 2 && recentHelpful >= 1) {
    return 'established';
  }

  // established → proven: score >= 5 AND multiple recent helpful
  if (bullet.maturity === 'established' && score >= 5 && recentHelpful >= 2) {
    return 'proven';
  }

  return bullet.maturity;
}

// Helper function
function daysSince(timestamp: string): number {
  const eventTime = new Date(timestamp).getTime();
  const now = Date.now();
  return (now - eventTime) / (1000 * 60 * 60 * 24);
}
```

PROMOTION CRITERIA:

Candidate → Established:
- Effective score >= 2 (net positive after decay & harmful weighting)
- At least 1 helpful mark in last 30 days (proves current relevance)

Established → Proven:
- Effective score >= 5 (strong positive signal)
- At least 2 helpful marks in last 30 days (consistent usage)

WHY TWO REQUIREMENTS:
Without recency check, old rules with decayed scores could still promote. We want to ensure rules are CURRENTLY useful, not just historically useful.

EXAMPLE SCENARIOS:

1. QUALIFIES for candidate → established:
   - 3 helpful marks in last week
   - 0 harmful marks
   - Effective score ≈ 1.5 (candidate maturity 0.5× multiplier)
   - Has recent helpful ✓
   - After promotion, score recalculated with 1.0× multiplier

2. DOES NOT qualify for established → proven:
   - 10 helpful marks from 6 months ago
   - Decayed score ≈ 2.5
   - Only 1 helpful in last 30 days (needs 2)
   - Stays established until more recent usage

3. RAPID promotion path:
   - New rule marked helpful 3 times in week 1
   - Promotes to established
   - Marked helpful 3 more times in week 2
   - Promotes to proven by day 14

INTEGRATION:
- Called by applyMaturityTransitions()
- Called after each curate cycle
- Pinned bullets can still be promoted
- Returns new maturity level or current if no change

DEPENDENCIES:
- getEffectiveScore()
- daysSince() helper
- PlaybookBullet.maturity field","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2025-12-07T16:45:21.423759-05:00","updated_at":"2025-12-07T21:15:58.744156-05:00","closed_at":"2025-12-07T21:14:24.785174-05:00"}
 {"id":"cass_memory_system-4hey","title":"[Foundation] Development workflow with hot reload","description":"Configure development workflow with hot reload for fast iteration during CASS Memory System development.

## Context
Developers need a fast feedback loop when working on CASS Memory System. Hot reload watches source files and automatically restarts the CLI when changes are detected, eliminating manual restart cycles.

## Technical Specification

### Development Commands:

#### Primary Development Mode:
bash
bun run src/cass-memory.ts [command] [args]

- Runs TypeScript source directly without compilation
- Fast startup (~50ms)
- Full TypeScript type checking
- No build step required

#### Hot Reload Mode:
bash
bun --watch run src/cass-memory.ts [command] [args]

- Watches all files in src/
- Automatically restarts on file changes
- Preserves command arguments
- Shows clear reload indicators

#### Type Check Mode:
bash
bun run typecheck
# or
tsc --noEmit

- Runs TypeScript compiler without emitting files
- Reports type errors
- Faster than full build
- Run before commits

#### Test Watch Mode:
bash
bun test --watch

- Runs tests on file changes
- Shows test results in real-time
- Supports filtering by test name

### Package.json Scripts:
json
{
  "scripts": {
    "dev": "bun run src/cass-memory.ts",
    "dev:watch": "bun --watch run src/cass-memory.ts",
    "typecheck": "tsc --noEmit",
    "typecheck:watch": "tsc --noEmit --watch",
    "test": "bun test",
    "test:watch": "bun test --watch",
    "lint": "eslint src/",
    "format": "prettier --write src/"
  }
}


### Workflow Examples:

#### Develop a New Command:
bash
# Terminal 1: Hot reload
bun --watch run src/cass-memory.ts doctor

# Terminal 2: Type checking
bun run typecheck:watch

# Terminal 3: Tests
bun test --watch


#### Quick Iteration:
bash
# Run command, see output, make changes, repeat
bun run src/cass-memory.ts status
# Edit src/commands/status.ts
bun run src/cass-memory.ts status  # See changes immediately


#### Debug Workflow:
bash
# Add console.log() to src/llm.ts
bun run src/cass-memory.ts reflect
# See logs immediately, no rebuild


### IDE Integration:

#### VS Code tasks.json:
json
{
  "version": "2.0.0",
  "tasks": [
    {
      "label": "Dev: Watch",
      "type": "shell",
      "command": "bun --watch run src/cass-memory.ts",
      "problemMatcher": []
    },
    {
      "label": "TypeCheck: Watch",
      "type": "shell",
      "command": "tsc --noEmit --watch",
      "problemMatcher": "-watch"
    }
  ]
}


#### VS Code launch.json:
json
{
  "version": "0.2.0",
  "configurations": [
    {
      "name": "Debug CASS Memory",
      "type": "bun",
      "request": "launch",
      "program": "/src/cass-memory.ts",
      "args": ["doctor"],
      "cwd": ""
    }
  ]
}


### Development Best Practices:

#### Before Starting Development:
bash
bun install          # Install dependencies
bun run typecheck    # Verify clean state


#### During Development:
- Use bun --watch for hot reload
- Keep typecheck running in separate terminal
- Run tests frequently with bun test
- Commit often with clear messages

#### Before Committing:
bash
bun run typecheck    # No type errors
bun test             # All tests pass
bun run build        # Binary builds successfully
./dist/cass-memory --version  # Binary works


## Reasoning

### Why Hot Reload:
1. Faster Feedback: See changes in < 1 second
2. Flow State: Minimize context switching
3. Rapid Prototyping: Try ideas quickly
4. Debugging: Add logs without rebuilding

### Why Bun for Development:
1. Fast Startup: Bun starts TypeScript in ~50ms
2. No Build Step: Run .ts files directly
3. Built-in Watch: --watch flag included
4. Hot Module Reload: Fast reloads

### Why Separate Type Checking:
1. Parallel Feedback: Types check while you run
2. Editor Integration: See errors in IDE
3. CI Validation: Same command in CI/local

### Why Test Watch Mode:
1. TDD Workflow: Write test, see it fail, make it pass
2. Regression Detection: Catch breaks immediately
3. Confidence: Know tests pass before commit

### Why Not Nodemon/ts-node:
1. Bun is Faster: Native TypeScript execution
2. Simpler Stack: One runtime instead of three tools
3. Better DX: Bun has better error messages
4. Future-Proof: Bun is the target runtime

## Acceptance Criteria

- bun run src/cass-memory.ts executes CLI without build
- bun --watch run src/cass-memory.ts reloads on file changes
- bun run typecheck reports type errors
- bun run typecheck:watch continuously checks types
- bun test runs all tests
- bun test --watch reruns tests on changes
- Changes to src/ files trigger reload in < 2 seconds
- Type errors show in terminal and IDE
- README documents development workflow
- CONTRIBUTING.md explains setup for new developers

## How This Serves the Universal Agent Memory System

Fast development workflow accelerates CASS Memory evolution:

1. Faster Iteration: Developers can try ideas in seconds, not minutes
2. Better Testing: Watch mode encourages TDD and comprehensive tests
3. Lower Barrier: New contributors can start developing immediately
4. Debugging: Quick feedback loop for fixing bugs
5. Experimentation: Easy to prototype new features
6. Quality: Type checking and tests run continuously
7. Documentation: Clear workflow guides new developers

Without hot reload and fast development tools, contributing to CASS Memory would be slow and frustrating. Fast feedback loops enable rapid innovation and keep the project moving forward.","status":"closed","priority":0,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2025-12-07T16:49:02.593086-05:00","updated_at":"2025-12-07T20:29:16.324233-05:00","closed_at":"2025-12-07T20:27:55.937505-05:00"}
